fp||cp|2|cs|3|ht|e|at|^b@2^*BHand Evaluation - Additional Gadgets ^*N

Welcome to 2 over 1 bid, play, discuss.

First, I want to start this week's class with a short lesson to introduce a useful convention.
The lesson is on hand evaluation and these observations come (mostly) from "Secrets of Winning Bridge", 
a classic written by Jeff Rubens (back in 1969).|
pg| ***** 4 ***** |


at|

First, we all know the "work" point count system: 4321.  4321 point count works best on balanced hands.   
It ignores 10's, 9's, and distribution. 
10's and 9's are important, and your hand will play better if you have more than the 2 you expect to be dealt.|
pg| ***** 5 ***** |


at|
Aces and Kings are worth more than their "work point count".     Why?  
They control suits.
Quacks (Queens and Jacks) are overvalued, because they don't come into their own until later in the play of a suit.|
pg| ***** 6 ***** |


at|

When you evaluate your hand, you don’t do it in a vacuum.  
The bidding and partner's hand enter into answering the question   "How good is my hand?".
Fitting cards in partner's suit are important.  Unsupported honors don’t pull their weight.  
A singleton king, for example, may be worthless to your side.|
pg| ***** 7 ***** |


at|

But we can look at our hand to get a pretty good idea of whether our hand is a "good" 13, or a "bad" 13   
For example, high cards in long suits improve your hand.
Example 1:   @SK10   @H9xxxx  @DAQ   @CJxxx  (10 HCP) is not nearly as good a hand as these 10:  
@Sxx  @HKQ109x  @Dxx  @cAJxx 
 
Rubens' FIRST PRINCIPLE:  "Other things being equal, honors are more valuable in your long suit than your short suit. The longer your suit is, the more valuable the honor." |
pg| ***** 8 ***** |


nt|
|fp||cp|2|cs|3|ht|b|at|^b@2^*BHand Evaluation - Additional Gadgets^*N (Cont)

Example 2:
Your hand is @SAx  @HKx  @DJxx  @C10xxxxx    What do you bid if pard opens 1NT?|
pg| ***** 9 ***** |


at|
At best, it's a raise to 2NT.
But @Sxx  @Hxx  @Dxxx  @CAKJ10xx is an almost automatic raise to 3.

The 2 hands have identically the same high card strength, but the concentration of strength in the club suit 
pretty much assures you of 5 tricks at NT,  6 if the @CQ is  friendly.

This leads to Rubens  SECOND  PRINCIPLE (Concentrated Strength): 

Other things being equal, honors in combination are worth more than isolated honors 
Example:  Suppose you have Axx and Kxx in 2 suits:  You have 1½ quick tricks, 
but  AKx  xxx   is 2 quick tricks. |
pg| ***** 10 ***** |


at|

How the auctions affects hand value:
Example 1:  You hold @cKQxx, a nice holding.   But suppose you knew that your pard was void in clubs....  
Now that holding is not so nice.

Example 2:  You have @SAKxxx  @Hxxx  @DQxx  @CAx and open 1@S  
Suppose partner splinters with 4@H.  
You would be happy to look for a spade slam.  
But suppose partner splinters with 4@D...  Now you will just sign off in 4@S|
pg| ***** 11 ***** |


at|

Some of you may be using the Help Suit Game Try (HSGT)   (in Europe, these may be known as "trial bids")
The idea is - we use "constructive" raises of 1M to 2M.  
If opener has a hand that evaluates to 16 or so points after the raise, she may want to get to game if 
there aren’t 3 quick losers in a side suit.|
pg| ***** 12 ***** |


nt||fp||cp|2|cs|3|at|^b@2

Example:  You open 1@S with   @sAJ10xx  @hxxx  @dAx  @cAQx
You have how many losers?|
pg| ***** 13 ***** |


at|
Your loser count is 7.  
How many losers would pard have for a 2@S (constructive) raise?
That is on a good hand.. you'd raise to 2@S with either  @sQxx  @hxx  @dKxxx  @cKxxx which has 8 losers 
or with @sQxx  @hxxx  @dKxx  @cKxxx - which has 9.  
So you want to be in  game with hand 1 but not with hand 2.|
pg| ***** 14 ***** |


at|
So a help-suit asks pard: "Do you have 3 quick losers in my help suit? (@h here)".
If responder can keep the losers to 2 in the help suit, she raises to game, otherwise, she signs off at 3. 
(MM: P, I have a 7-loser hand, but if you can make it a 6 loser hand with shortness in hearts,
and you have an 8-loser hand yourself => 24 - ( 6+8 = 14) => 10 winners.  ) 
So they are useful to get you to close games. |
pg| ***** 15 ***** |


at|

^*BHand Evaluation - Additional Gadgets^*N (Cont)
There are lots of variations on this idea, and here is a gadget that has a lot of support among tournament players.
It is part of the Washington Standard (the system played a lot here in the DC area) 
put together by World Champion and Hall of Fame player Steve Robinson.

Suppose that you use "constructive" major suit raises (3 card support, 7-9 HCP);  
The auction starts off 1@S - 2@S. 
If opener bids a new suit at the 3 level, it's a game try of some sort 
(most people use "help suit" game tries, some use "short suit" game tries).|
pg| ***** 16 ***** |


at|
 
After a raise of 1@S or 1@H to 2@S/@H, opener rebids 2NT (alertable!). 
This is NOT looking to play in NT, but rather to find out where pard has shape. 
Responder bids a short suit (xx or shorter). Opener now has a better idea of whether her high cards are working.
 
Example: Opener has  @sAQJxx  @hxxx  @dKQx  @cAx 
If responder has something like  @sKxx  @hxxx  @dJxx  @cKxxx, you do not wish to be in game, 
but with  @sKxx  @hxx  @dJxxx  @cKxxx, 4@S doesn't need more than a 3-2 @s split (and no diamond ruff).|
pg| ***** 17 ***** |


nt||fp||cp|2|cs|3|at|^b@2
So opener bids 2NT (alertable) -- Responder signs off with 3@S on the first hand (@sKxx,@Hxxx, @DJxx,@CKxxx). 
(Opener could open 1NT with the first hand, but some people will open 1@S with that hand)
On the second hand, responder bids 3@H (also alertable - @sKxx,@Hxx, @DJxxx,@CKxxx).
Opener now knows to bid 4@S, since there is no wastage in hearts, 
AND dummy will be able to ruff the third round @h. 

Now, there is a second advantage for using this gadget.  
When opener bids a new suit at the 3 level, it shows a better hand than a simple game try, for example: 
@sAQ10xx  @Hxx  @DKQJx  @CAx|
pg| ***** 18 ***** |


at|

Cliff228: Can you use both HSGT and SSGT?
mitche:  You should pick 1 or the other.  Some like SSGT,  some HSGT - 
My preference is to use SSGT, but most of my pards are not quite that enlightened :)
Reason for SSGT - if responder has good stuff in it, she can escape to 3NT. 
Example:  @sQxx  @HAK10xx  @Dxx  @CAJx   makes SSGT and if pard has something like: 
@SJx  @HQxx  @DKQ10x  @Cxxxx   can bid 3NT.|
